PhD Thesis

Mathematical Framework and Hierarchical Control for Sovereignty‑Constrained Multi‑Constellation LEO Satellite Networks

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

This thesis presents a complete mathematical framework and hierarchical control architecture for the intelligent orchestration of heterogeneous Low‑Earth‑Orbit satellite constellations. We address the fundamental challenge of coordinating multiple autonomous constellations—each with its own operator, sovereignty constraints, and physical dynamics—while ensuring end‑to‑end quality of service. The core contributions are: (1) a temporal hypergraph model that integrates orbital mechanics with time‑varying network topology, including a rigorous proof of link existence based on two‑line element data; (2) a distributed optimisation framework based on the Alternating Direction Method of Multipliers (ADMM) that explicitly enforces operator‑level sovereignty constraints; (3) a multi‑agent reinforcement learning system using graph neural networks and a centralised critic that achieves scalable, adaptive routing under uncertainty, with formal policy improvement guarantees; and (4) a stability analysis via switched hybrid automata and Lyapunov methods, proving exponential stability of the closed‑loop system under bounded perturbations. The framework is validated through large‑scale simulations using realistic orbital data and traffic traces, achieving a 24.8% reduction in latency and a 15.8% improvement in energy efficiency compared to state‑of‑the‑art baselines. A proof‑of‑concept emulation with software‑defined radios confirms the feasibility of key control loops. The thesis concludes with a discussion of the path toward standardisation in 3GPP Non‑Terrestrial Networks and future extensions to non‑cooperative settings.

Keywords: LEO satellite constellations, multi‑agent reinforcement learning, distributed optimisation, sovereignty constraints, temporal graphs, hybrid systems, network orchestration.

